  "datePublished": "2025-12-31",
  "description": "An ∞-category is a category-like structure with morphisms in all dimensions: objects, morphisms between objects, 2-morphisms between morphisms, 3-morphisms between 2-morphisms, and so on, with coherent composition at every level. Where an ordinary category has only objects and arrows, an ∞-category has arrows between arrows at every height.\nSeveral equivalent models make this idea precise. A quasi-category (or weak Kan complex) is a simplicial set with inner horn fillers. A Segal category or complete Segal space uses simplicial spaces. A simplicially enriched category uses enrichment over simplicial sets. These models are all equivalent in a precise sense and form the basis of higher category theory.\n",
  "name": "Infinity Category",
